 We are very grateful to you who are using 'Entry'. 
Recently we have agreed to transfer the ownership of Entry web site, which has been operated for public interest purposes, to the 'Connect Foundation'.

Menus.entry_content_one: Bring your imagination to life with ENTRY.
Menus.entry_content_two: Create games, animations, media art, and other cool projects!
Menus.entry_content_three: Create projects and share with your friends. Enter the exciting world of ENTRY!
Menus.learn_problem_solving: Various learning contents and mini challenges are available for you in the < Learn > section. Solve mini challenges by coding. Watch fun videos and learn to program.
Menus.make_contents: In the <Create> section, create your own program with block-based programming language. Create simulation programs to test laws of Physics. Create animation program with your favorite characters. Bring your imagination to life with Entry.
Menus.and_content: There is no limit to what you can create. You can experiment physical laws you’ve learned in science class, create animations featuring your favorite characters, and even make your own games.
Menus.explore_contents: The <Explore> section, showcases thousands of projects created and shared by the Entry community. Try out the fun and creative projects, see how they are coded, and improve them. You can also cooperate with your peers to create exciting projects.
Menus.why_software: Why is learning to code important?
Menus.speak_obama_contents: Learning these skills isn’t just important for your future. It’s important for our country’s future.
Menus.billgates_contents: Learning to write programs stretches your mind, and helps you think better, creates a way of thinking about things that I think is helpful in all domains.
Menus.eric_contents: For most people on Earth, the digital revolution hasn't even started yet. Within the next 10 years, all that will change. Let's get the whole world coding!
Menus.sandbug_contents: An understanding of computer science is becoming increasingly essential in today’s world. Our national competitiveness depends upon our ability to educate our children—and that includes our girls—in this critical field.
Menus.view_entry_tools: Introducing Entry’s unplugged games for teaching programming.
Menus.solve_problem_content: Mini challenges will help you learn the basics of programming.
Menus.find_extra_contents: Entry bot is special robot created one day at the Rutz Robot Toy Factory during a blackout. Help him find his missing parts and escape the factory while learning to code.
Menus.software_play_contents: Watch ‘Let’s Play Software’ , follow along the tutorials and learn to create fun programs.
Menus.resources_contents: Get various Entry educational materials for free
Menus.sw_camp: Software Creativity Camp, Ministry of Science, ICT and Future Planning
Menus.sw_contents_one: This guidebook is for elementary students learn physical computing over a 5-lesson course. Students learn to use Entry and create images and stoires. In the final section, students use Arduino to create a musical keyboard
Menus.sw_camp_detail: Ministry of Science, ICT and Future Planning Software Creation Camp
Menus.sw_contents_two: This textbook allows middle school students to experience ENTRY and physical computing over a 5-lesson course. Students learn how to use ENTRY, and create a maze game and quiz program. In the final section, students use Arduino and keyboard to steer a car.
Menus.sw_contents_three: This is a teacher’s guide for starting computing classes in schools.  It contains a variety of unplugged activities and lesson plans using clips from ‘Let’s play, Software!’broadcasts.
Menus.teacher_teaching: Teacher’s Guide (for elementary grades 5-6 and above)
Menus.sw_contents_four: This textbook allows students to learn about computing in a fun and playful way through a variety of unplugged activities such as ENTRY Board, and teaches students the basic principles of programming via ENTRY Course Mode. Once they have got down the basics, students learn how to create stories, games, artistic works, and applications using ENTRY. The textbook allows students to create and present their own software.
Menus.ct_text_5_content: This teacher's guide contains 8 problem solving tasks. Each task is designed to reflect the revised National Curriculum and contains interdisciplinary themes. Cultivate computational thinking skills.
Menus.ct_text_6_content: 실생활의 문제를 해결하자는 테마로 준비된 총 8개의 학습콘텐츠가 담긴 교사용 지도안입니다. 각 콘텐츠는 개정된 교육과정을 반영한 타교과와의 연계를 통해 다양한 문제를 만나고 해결해볼 수 있도록 설계되었습니다.  아이들이 컴퓨팅 사고력을 갖춘 융합형 인재가 될 수 있도록 지금 적용해보세요!

Menus.sensorboard_contents: Using Arduino no longer requires building a circuit using lots of wires. With ENTRY Board, you can use LED lights, temperature, sound, light sensors, a slider, and switches by simply mounting it onto an Arduino board. Now anyone can easily create their own unique projects using ENTRY Board!
Menus.unplugged_contents: Learn the principles of programming through Entry-bot Board Game. By helping Entrybot escape the factory, you can learn to think like a computer scientist.
Menus.entrybot_cardgame_contents: 12 different types of bombs appear at the city of Entry! Dismantle the bombs one at a time and learn the basics of programming. By using the concepts of sequence, repetition and conditionals, save the City and become a hero!

Menus.escape_guide_2: ENTRY Bot is missing too many parts to make it far. Help him find his parts as he makes his way out the factory!
Menus.escape_guide_3: I’ve finally escaped the factory! But it’s still a long way to the village. I think I’m fixed up enough to make it there without too much difficulty. Hey, what’s that robot?

Menus.space_guide_1: ENTRY Bot has finally completed his exploration of distant space. He’s trying to make his way back home to Earth, but his path is being blocked by a bunch of space rocks! Help ENTRY Bot make it back to Earth safely!
Menus.space_guide_2: It’s finally time to return to Earth! I can’t wait to get back and rest! Tell me the positions of the rocks ahead so I can navigate through them! I’ll go the way you tell me to!

Menus.maze_1_intro: Hi. I’m ENTRY Bot. I’m about to save my injured friends and I need your help. Help me save my friends! First, set up the ‘Move forward one space’ block and press ‘Start’.
Menus.maze_1_content: How do I move ENTRY Bot?
Menus.maze_1_detail:
1. Take a block from the Block Box and connect it with the ‘When Start is pressed’ block. 
 2. Press Start once you have finished assembling. 
 3. I will move in the order of your assembled blocks from top to bottom.
Menus.maze_2_intro: Alright! You’ve saved the first of my friends! Now let’s save my next friend. Oh! There’s a beehive in the way! Use the Jump Over block to avoid the beehive and save my friend!
Menus.maze_2_content_1: How do I get around obstacles?
Menus.maze_2_detail_1:
Sometimes your path may be blocked by an obstacle. 
 When there’s an obstacle in your path, you need to use the ‘Jump Over’ block.
Menus.maze_2_content_2: How do I move ENTRY Bot?
Menus.maze_2_detail_2:
1. Take a block from the Block Box and connect it with the ‘When Start is pressed’ block. 
 2. Press Start once you have finished assembling. 
 3. I will move in the order of your assembled blocks from top to bottom.
Menus.maze_3_intro: Awesome! Now let’s go save another friend! How about we use the ‘Repeat’ block that my other friend gave use? You can easily repeat the same movements over again using the ‘Repeat’ block! Try changing the number of times to repeat.
Menus.maze_3_content: How do I use the ‘Repeat (3)’ block?
Menus.maze_3_detail:
To perform the same action/s more than once, you need to use the ‘Repeat’ block. 
 Put the blocks that you want to repeat inside the Repeat box and select the number of times you want to repeat.
Menus.maze_4_intro: Super! Not too many robot friends left to save now. Take us to my friend by using the ‘Jump Over’ block on repeat while also evading the beehive!
Menus.maze_4_content: How do I use the ‘Repeat (3)’ block?
Menus.maze_4_detail:
To perform the same action/s more than once, you need to use the ‘Repeat’ block. 
 Put the blocks that you want to repeat inside the Repeat box and select the number of times you want to repeat.
Menus.maze_5_intro: Cool! Now let’s try using the ‘Repeat’ block and ‘IF’ block together! Using the ‘IF’ block, you can turn in a direction where there are no walls when you come across a wall. Well then, shall we set off to save my friend?
Menus.maze_5_detail_1:
You can determine what action to take when you come across a {IMAGE}. 
 The blocks are used only when you come across a {IMAGE}. 
 If there is none, the block is not used.
Menus.maze_5_content_2: How do I use the ‘Repeat until’block?
Menus.maze_5_detail_2:
Using the ‘Repeat until’block, you can determine until when a specified action is repeated. 
 Just put the blocks you want to repeat inside the ‘Repeat until’ block. 
 Then, the repetition will stop when you reach the space where the {IMAGE} is located.
Menus.maze_6_intro: Only one friend left! Just do as we’ve practiced and you’ll succeed! Now, let’s go save him!
Menus.maze_6_detail_1:
You can determine what action to take when you come across a {IMAGE}. 
 The blocks are used only when you come across a {IMAGE}. 
 If there is none, the block is not used.
Menus.maze_6_content_2: How do I use the ‘Repeat until’block?
Menus.maze_6_detail_2:
Using the ‘Repeat until’block, you can determine until when a specified action is repeated. 
 Just put the blocks you want to repeat inside the ‘Repeat until’ block. 
 Then, the repetition will stop when you reach the space where the {IMAGE} is located.
Menus.maze_operation1_1_desc: Hi, I'm Entrybot, the robot dog. Give me commands to reach the mission goals. You can learn about the mission when you begin under \'Goals.\'
Menus.maze_operation1_2_desc: Once you learn your goal, you need to give me commands. \’Command Box\’ is where the commands reside. You can create commands using mouse and keyboard. With the mouse, you can click or drag the commands to create instructions.
Menus.maze_operation1_2_textset_1: How to click on the commands
Menus.maze_operation1_2_textset_2: How to drag and drop commands
Menus.maze_operation1_3_desc: If you want to use the keyboard to give commands, type in the commands in the \’Command Box.\’ When you type in the commands, be careful not to ommit () and ;
Menus.maze_operation1_4_desc:
Once you have finished inputting the commands, click [Run.]
I will move according to your code once you click [Run.]
If you want to know more about each command, check out the [Command guide.]
Menus.maze_operation7_title: STEP 7 - How repeat works (repeat number of times)
Menus.maze_operation7_1_desc: Repeating the same command over and over is a cumbersome task. Simplify the command using the repeat commands.
Menus.maze_operation7_2_desc:
Then let's look at how we can simplify commands that repeat.
First, click the repeat command. Then change the number ini<1
Then insert the commands to repeat within { }
Menus.maze_operation7_3_desc: For example, this command executes move(); 10 times. It is the same as command
Menus.maze_operation7_4_desc:
When using commands, make sure to spell the commands correctly within { }
and that you don't forget ’;'.
Learn more about the commands in the 'command guide'
Menus.study_maze_operation8_title: STEP 4 - How repeat works (repeat number of times)
Menus.study_maze_operation16_title: STEP 4 - How repeat works (repeat number of times)
Menus.study_maze_operation1_title: STEP 1 - How repeat works (repeat number of times)
Menus.maze_operation9_1_desc:
We learned about repeating for set number of times.
This time, let's explore commands for repeating continuously.
When you use this command, the action will be executed until end of the mission.
Insert commands to be repeated within ({ }).
Menus.maze_operation9_2_desc: move(); right(); until end of mission. It is the same as command
Menus.maze_operation9_3_desc: Make sure to spell the commands correctly within { } and make sure ‘true' isn't missing! You can learn more about this command in the 'command guide'
Menus.maze_operation10_1_desc:
We learned about repeating commands until end of the mission.
This time, let's explore the commands that are only executed under certain conditions.
As you can see in , using conditional statement can make commands more efficient.
Menus.maze_operation10_2_desc:
conditional statement can be split into condition and commands to be executed when met with the condition.
First, let's look at the conditions. Insert the condition within ( ) that follows ‘if'.
For example if(front == ‘wall') means, \’if there is a wall in front of me.\’
Menus.maze_operation10_3_desc: Now let's explore commands to execute when met with the condition. These commands are tied within curly braces {} and are executed when met with the given condition.When condition is not met, the commands are ignored.Let's look at an example . If the condition is 'when a wall is in front of me', and the condition is met, then I execute the commands within the braces and turn right following the command right();
Menus.maze_operation10_4_desc:
The conditional statements are often used with repeat commands.
Go straight and turn only when met with a wall.
I can create commands in the order of
Menus.maze_operation10_1_textset_2:
move 2 forward
turn right,
move 3 forward
turn right, move forward…
Menus.maze_operation10_1_textset_4:
Go forward
'when met with a wall’
turn right!
Menus.maze_operation10_2_textset_2: commands to execute when condition is met
Menus.maze_operation10_3_textset_2: commands to execute when condition is met
Menus.maze_operation10_4_textset_2:
Go forward
until met with a wall
Menus.maze_operation10_4_textset_3:
Go forward
until met with a wall
then turn right
Menus.maze_operation15_1_desc:
It is a cumbersome task to type out the commands that are used often.
Give a name to the set of commands that are used often.
Then call the set of commands by its name to create commands conveniently.
These sets commands are called 'functions'. Now let's explore what functions are.
Menus.maze_operation15_2_desc:
Using a function involves process of creating a function by grouping a set of functions, and calling the set of commands by 'call function’.
Let's take a look at the process of defining a function.To define a function, give a function name and set of commands to execute.
First input ‘function' and then give the function name. This time, I'll call it promise.
Once you've given it a name, insert (). Then type in ({ }).Once you insert the commands within these brackets, you have finished defining a function!
Menus.maze_operation15_3_desc:
Take a look at this command. I created a function called promise
When I call this function, then the commands within the brackets({}) will execute
move();
move();
left();
Menus.maze_operation15_4_desc:
To call and execute functions, input the name of the functions, then add '();' behind it.
So to call a function called 'promise', I need to type promise();
to execute the function.
When I make commands like , the program will execute as that of
To use the function, define function as and call it.

Menus.maze_text_content_1: 명령어를 사용해서 나를 부품 상자까지 이동시켜줘!
Menus.maze_text_content_3: Nice! I see another part over there. The path is twisted but I can get there using the 'right();', 'left();' commands.
Menus.maze_text_content_4: I can move smoothly now. Take me to my parts using the commands we've learned so far.
Menus.maze_text_content_5: Wow! Two parts! Let's collect them both so I can recover faster.
Menus.maze_text_content_6: Last part! I'll recover fully with that last piece. You'll help me, right?
Menus.maze_text_content_7: I'm feeling great! I can repeat tasks without stress now. Oh no! What is that robot in front of us? I think it needs help! Use 'for' command to get to the friend!
Menus.maze_text_content_8: Excellent! I was able to rescue my robot friend thanks to you. I see another friend over there. Be careful. There are beehives to avoid. You can do it! Let's use the 'for' command to get to my friend.
Menus.maze_text_content_9: Use 'while' instead of 'for' to repeat until we've accomplished our goal. Take me to my friend.
Menus.maze_text_content_10: Now we have 'if' command. Use 'if' and 'while' to let me know which way to turn.
Menus.maze_text_content_11: Great! Let's do this once more. Tell me when to turn left.
Menus.maze_text_content_12: There are beehives scattered in the pathway. Tell me when to jump over.
Menus.maze_text_content_13: So many friends need help! Let's go help them
Menus.maze_text_content_14: More friends to rescue! Let's first try going around those square blocks and repeat to get to all of my friends.
Menus.maze_text_content_15: I'm tired from moving so much. I've grouped the commands that are often used into 'functions'. Use functions to get me to my battery!
Menus.maze_text_content_16: Excellent! Create functions and take me to my battery!
Menus.maze_text_content_17: Great job! Let's create functions with 'jump()
Menus.maze_text_content_18: The pathway is complex this time. But no worries! Just tell me when to use 'left()
Menus.maze_text_content_19: The functions are already defined! However, it seems difficult to get to the battery using only the functions. Let's try mixing functions and commands to get to the battery.
Menus.maze_text_content_20: You've done a fantastic job so far! After I retrieve that last battery, I will no longer need charging. Help me get to the battery using the functions so I can live free forever!
Menus.maze_content_1: Hi, I'm Entrybot. I'm trying to escape from this factory but first, I have to fix myself. Will you help me fetch my parts? Assemble 'Move forward' block and press Start.
Menus.maze_content_2: Very good! I'm feeling much better! I see my part over there but I might get electrocuted if I don't be careful. Let's use 'jump over obstacle' block to get to the part.
Menus.maze_content_3: Great! My part is right over there. The path is a bit twisted but I can get there using 'rotate' blocks. You'll help me, right?
Menus.maze_content_4: Nice! I can almost move freely now. Let's get the part using 'rotate' and 'jump' blocks.
Menus.maze_content_5: Wow! Two parts! Let's get them both so I can restore my health faster.
Menus.maze_content_6: Thanks to you I'm feeling much better! I'm able to get better with those parts. You'll help me, right?
Menus.maze_content_7: I'm feeling great! I can repeat the same task without trouble now. Oh! Do you see the robot over there? I think she might need help. Let's go help her out. Bring me to her by changing the number of 'repeat's
Menus.maze_content_8: Excellent! I was able to rescue my pal! It looks like another one of my friends need help. Be careful there are beehives. Be sure to jump over the beehives! Can you do it? Help me reach her using the 'repeat' block.
Menus.maze_content_9: Instead of repeating a task for set number of times, I can repeat until I reach my robot pal instead! Help me save my friend!
Menus.maze_content_10: Now we can use the 'if' block. Help me use the 'if' block to turn at right timing.
Menus.maze_content_11: Let's try it again! Let me know when to turn left.
Menus.maze_content_12: There are beehives all over the place. Tell me when to jump!
Menus.maze_content_13: My friends need help! Let's go help them!
Menus.maze_content_14: More friends need rescue! Let's first go around the small square and repeat it to rescue all my friends.
Menus.maze_content_15: Now I can memorize blocks that are used repeatedly. Promise blocks are the ones that I was able to memorize. I'm a bit tired from moving so much. Help me refill my battery using the Promise feature!
Menus.maze_content_16: Great! Tell me which blocks are used often and put them under the Promise block!
Menus.maze_content_17: Nice! Use Promise blocks to help me get my battery. Make sure to insert 'Jump' blocks in the Promise block.
Menus.maze_content_18: The path looks complex! We can get through this if we turn left and right at the right time.
Menus.maze_content_19: The 'Promise' if already set for us! However, we can't use the Promise blocks as is. I'll need to use the Promise blocks at the right timing to get the battery.
Menus.maze_content_20: Excellent! You've done great so far! After the final battery, I won't need to charge any more. So help me get the last battery using the Promise so I can live forever free!
Menus.maze_content_21: 안녕? 나는 엔트리 봇이야. 지금 많은 친구들이 내 도움을 필요로 하고 있어. 반복하기를 이용해서 친구들을 도울수 있게 데려다 줘!
Menus.maze_content_22: 고마워! 이번에는 벌집을 뛰어넘어서 친구를 구하러 갈 수 있게 도와줘!
Menus.maze_content_23: 좋아! 이번에는 친구 로봇한테 갈 때까지 반복하기를 이용해서 친구를 도울 수 있게 도와줘!
Menus.maze_content_24: 안녕! 나는 엔트리 봇이야. 지금 나는 너무 오래 움직여서 배터리를 채워야 해. 약속 불러오기를 써서 배터리를 채울 수 있도록 도와줘!
Menus.maze_content_25: 멋져! 이번에는 여러 약속을 불러와서 배터리가 있는 곳까지 가보자!
Menus.maze_content_26: 좋아! 이제 약속할 블록을 나한테 가르쳐줘! 약속하기 블록 안에 자주 쓰일 블록을 넣으면 돼!
Menus.maze_content_27: 지금은 미리 약속이 정해져 있어. 그런데, 약속을 쓰기위해서는 내가 갈 방향을 보고 약속을 사용해야해. 도와줄거지?
Menus.maze_content_28: 드디어 마지막이야! 약속을 이용하여 마지막 배터리를 얻을 수 있게 도와줘!
Menus.ai_content_1: Hi! I'm Entrybot. I just completed the space exploration mission and I need to return to Earth but it's not easy because of the asteroids. Could you help me return home? I have radars on top, front and back of the spaceship to detect how far an obstacle exists. It'll help you make smart decisions.
Menus.ai_content_2: Thank you! I was able to avoid the asteroids without trouble. There are more asteroids this time. Let's try avoiding them!
Menus.ai_content_3: Great! I was able to safely avoid the asteroids! There are more asteroids now! Don't worry though! I have the 'repeat' block. Place blocks in the 'repeat' block so we can get to the destination!
Menus.ai_content_4: Excellent! It's so much more easier to avoid the asteroids using the repeat blocks! However, it's tiring driving the spaceship at all times! I can use the radar to sense what's coming. Help avoid the asteroids using the radar.
Menus.ai_content_5: Nice! I'm so glad we've come this far. The radar will tell how far an object exists. Let's use the radar to avoid the asteroids! Move forward until we come close to an asteroid then avoid!
Menus.ai_content_6: Great job! You're using radar to avoid tha asteroids. Use multiple radars to avoid the asteroids.
Menus.ai_content_7: We're getting close to Earth! I want to go in a safer path if possible. It must be safer to move farther from the asteroids, right? Compare the distance to the obstacle using the radar on the top and bottom of the spaceship to move to a safer direction.
Menus.ai_content_8: Excellent! We're safely cruising through space. Oh! What is that? That's looks like my special energy! Let's collect the special energy on our way!
Menus.ai_content_9: Very good! We're almost there. The path is filled with asteroid. But don’t worry! We can get rid of the obstacles using the special item.
Menus.ai_content_10: Good! I can see Earth! But now it's impossible to see the asteroids ahead! I'm not worried though. We can avoid the asteroids with more caution. Let's go home!
Menus.maze_hints_detail_1:
1. Drag the block you want to use and place it under 'When Run'
2. Once finished, click 'Run'
3. I will follow the block instructions step by step, reading them from top to bottom
Menus.maze_hints_content_2: What do I do when I come across an obstacle?
Menus.maze_hints_detail_2:
On your pathway, you might come across obstacles.
Use 'jump over' block to jump over the obstacle.
Menus.maze_hints_content_3: How do I use repeat (3) times block?
Menus.maze_hints_detail_3:
If you want to repeat an action multiple times, use 'repeat ~times' block. 
Place the blocks you want to repeat within the 'repeat ~times' block and input how many times to repeat.
Menus.maze_hints_content_4: How do I use 'repeat until ~' block?
Menus.maze_hints_detail_4:
Use 'repeat until~do' block to set until when an action should be performed. 
Place the blocks you want to repeat within 'repeat until~' block.
Then once met with {image}, repeat will stop.
Menus.maze_hints_detail_5:
Using 'If {image}' block, you can designate what action should follow when met with {image}.
Blocks within the 'If {image}' will only execute when met with {image}.
Menus.maze_hints_content_6: How does 'Until met with all ~' block work?
Menus.maze_hints_detail_6:
Repeat blocks within 'Until met with all ~' block until met with all {tile}.
 Once met with all {tile} repeat will stop.
Menus.maze_hints_detail_7:
Look at the path that I should travel. See the 4 small squares?
First create blocks that will take me around the square and repeat.
Menus.maze_hints_content_8: What is 'Functions/ Call Functions'? How do I use them?
Menus.maze_hints_detail_8:
Put the most often used sets of blocks under 'Function'. 
Once you create functions, use 'Call Function' to use it as often as needed.
Menus.ai_hints_content_1_1: Avoid asteroids and help me get to Earth
Menus.ai_hints_detail_1_1: Avoid asteroids and help me get to Earth
Menus.ai_hints_detail_1_2:
1. Drag out blocks from the block box and connect is with the 'when run' block
2. Once finished assembling blocks, click 'Run'
3. I'll move according to your block instructions.
Menus.ai_hints_content_1_3: How do I move the entrybot?
Menus.ai_hints_detail_1_3:
I can move up, forward or below.
When creating instructions, make sure I avoid the asteroids.
If you send me out of the screen, I can be lost in space forever! So be careful.
Menus.ai_hints_content_2_1: Use repeat blocks to avoid the asteroids.
Menus.ai_hints_detail_2_1: Use repeat blocks to avoid the asteroids.
Menus.ai_hints_detail_2_2:
Geez! It's a long way home so putting blocks together one by one is too tiresome. Let's try using the repeat block.
Once you group the blocks under the repeat block, you can shorten the length of the blocks!
Menus.ai_hints_content_3_1: Help me avoid the asteroids using the 'if' block
Menus.ai_hints_detail_3_2:
Using 'if~ in front/ else' block can help me check if there are asteroids in front of me and help me avoid them.
If there's an asteroid in front of me, then blocks under 'if' will execute or if there isn't an asteroid, the blocks under 'else' will execute.
Tell me which way to go depending on whether there's an asteroid to avoid or not.
Menus.ai_hints_content_4_1: Learn to use the radar to avoid the asteroids.
Menus.ai_hints_detail_4_1: Learn to use the radar to avoid the asteroids.
Menus.ai_hints_content_4_2: What is a radar and how can I use it?
Menus.ai_hints_detail_4_2:
Radar tells me how far an object exists from where I am located. 
If there is an object in front of me, the front radar will show '1'.
Also, radar can become a powerful tool when used with 'if <true>/else' block.
For example, when the distance to an object in front of me shows value greater than 1, then I am able to move forward safely.
 However, if not, then I can go above or under to avoid it.
Menus.ai_hints_detail_4_3:
if <true> block/ else' block executes blocks under 'if' when condition is met and executes blocks under 'else' when condition is not met.
Think about how you want to move at different situations and create a condition within <true> block.
Remember that when condition is met and blocks under 'if' are executed, then the blocks under 'else' will be ignored.
Menus.ai_hints_content_5_1: Use the radar to help me avoid the asteroids.
Menus.ai_hints_detail_5_1: Use the radar to help me avoid the asteroids.
Menus.ai_hints_content_5_2: How does nested if blocks work?
Menus.ai_hints_detail_5_2:
I can nest 'if ~/else' block within 'if ~/else' block. This will help me make smart decisions in various situations.
For example, I can act according to whether an asteroid is in my path or not, then when I'm met with and asteroid, I can decide whether to go under or above.
Menus.ai_hints_content_6_1: How do I compare the values given by radar above and radar below?
Menus.ai_hints_detail_6_1:
([above]radar) block shows distance to an object above.
You can use this block to check which asteroid above or below exist further away.
When deciding which way to avoid the asteroid, it'll be a smarter move to go in the direction where the asteroid is further away.
Menus.ai_hints_content_7_1: Use the item to avoid the asteroids.
Menus.ai_hints_detail_7_1: Use the item to avoid the asteroids.
Menus.ai_hints_content_7_2: What can I do by checking the object name in front of me?
Menus.ai_hints_detail_7_2:
To gain a special item, you need to check where the item is located.
Use 'object [above] is [item]' block.
By using this block, you can figure out where the item is located and move towards it.
Menus.ai_hints_content_8_1: Use the item to help me avoid the asteroids.
Menus.ai_hints_detail_8_1: Use the item to help me avoid the asteroids.
Menus.ai_hints_content_8_2: How do I gain special item and use it?
Menus.ai_hints_detail_8_2:
Even though you succeed in avoiding the asteroids, when the pathway is lined with asteroids, there is no way to avoid them. In this case, use the 'use item' block.
It will get rid of all blocks in front.
However, you can only use this block when you've gained the item by passing through the item.
Menus.ai_hints_content_9_1: Use all your skills and knowledge to go as far as you can.
Menus.ai_hints_detail_9_1: Use all your skills and knowledge to go as far as you can.
Menus.ai_hints_content_9_2: How do I use the 'and' block?
Menus.ai_hints_detail_9_2: and' block can fit in many conditions. When all conditions in the 'and' block is met, then the blocks will be executed. If one of them is false, the whole 'and' statement will be false and the blocks will not be executed.
Menus.maze_text_goal_1: Use move();  command to move me to the part box!
Menus.maze_text_goal_2: Use jump();  command to avoid obstacles.
Menus.maze_text_goal_3: Use left(); right(); command to take me to my parts.

Msgs.journal_henesys_no1_content: This is the first journal for Henesys. Today, I almost fell trying to jump on the way to the blacksmith’s house. He’s important in Henesys. Why did he make such a big hole in front of his yard? I don't think there’s anyone who can jump through these holes unless it's a great monster like me! let’s go to that restaurant. It’s supposed to be good!
Msgs.journal_henesys_no2_content: I really did eat too much. The meat in that restaurant was really delicious. How could it be so tender? But the bread next door wasn’t great. The chef seemed to be always playing around, saying he’s “learning how to cook better.” He should use that time to get some more practice. Now that I’ve filled my belly, time to start a full-scale adventure!
Msgs.journal_ellinia_no1_content: Phew, I sat on an Orange Mushroom without even knowing. I guess that’s a good reason to get mad... But piling on me was too much! They’re a scary bunch. No wonder the slimes had a hard time. No need to worry, though! Yours truly took care of it! Now that the slimes are my friends, I’m gonna continue the adventure into this gorgeous forest.
Msgs.journal_ellinia_no2_content: My adventurous friend, Royal Fairy, told me there are some scary rumors going on around Elnath. I wonder what that is? I’m supposed to play with my friends at home tonight, so I’ll ask then. I can’t wait!  But what should I wear ... I don’t think anything is going to fit because I got bigger... Well, I’m always cute, so no matter what I wear, everyone will love it!
Msgs.journal_elnath_no1_content: Oh, my gosh! So this is \"snow\" I heard so much about, huh? It's always spring where I live, so this is my first snow. I wasn't paying much attention because I was busy fighting the monsters, but now I see the whole world is so white and cold! I thought it’d be tasty, but it's flavorless. I wish I can bring some back, but there's no way. Oh, too bad.
Msgs.journal_elnath_no2_content: Eww, I accidentally ate coal dust! Those bad monsters! Least they could do is run away quietly, but they just had to spread coal all over. Thanks to them, my shiny, fluffy pink skin is getting dirtier. I need to get out of here and take a clean bath. Adventure is nice, but no self-respecting monster should walk around looking this dirty.

Helper.boolean_basic_operator:
Compare the two values entered.
= : If the value on the left and the value on the right are the same, it is judged as 'true'.
!= : If the value on the left and the value on the right are not the same, it is judged as 'true'.
> : If the value on the left is more than the value on the right, it is judged as 'true'.
< : If the value on the left is less than the value on the right, it is judged as 'true'.
≥ : If the value on the left is more than or equal to the value on the right, it is judged as 'true'
.≤ : If the value on the left is less than or equal to the value on the right, it is judged as 'true'.
Helper.function_create: Define a function by placing frequently used sets of blocks under this block. Place [name] next to [Define function] to give function a name. Pass on number of text values by placing [numeric/text value] block. Pass on boolean value of true or false by placing the [boolean value] block.
Helper.function_field_label: Place inside the [Define function] block and gives function a name.
Helper.function_field_string: Place inside the [Define function] block and the result depends on the input numeric/text value. Grab/copy the [numberic/text value] block in the [Define function] block and use its value in function.
Helper.function_field_boolean: Place inside the [Define function] block and the result depends on the boolean value of true or false. Grab/copy the [numberic/text value] block in the [Define function] block and use its value in function.
Helper.function_general: This is current function block or function blocks created so far.
Helper.boolean_and: Checks whether both conditions are true.
Helper.boolean_or: Checks whether at least one of the two conditions is true.
Helper.boolean_not:

Helper.robotis_carCont_sensor_value:
Left connected sensor : the value of contact (1), non-contact (0).
Right contact sensor: the value of contact (1), non-contact (0).
Final number of sound detection : the value of the number of last live sound detection.
Number of live sound detection : increases by 1 when it detects the next sound within 1 second.
Right infrared sensor: the value is larger when it's closer to an object.
Value of left infrared sensor calibration : the calibration value of the infrared sensor.
Value of right infrared sensor calibration : the calibration value of the infrared sensor.
(*Calibration value - control value of infrared sensor)
Helper.robotis_carCont_cm_led:

Helper.robotis_carCont_cm_calibration: Sets the controlling value of infrared sensor (http://support.robotis.com/ko/: automobile robot> 2. B. control infrared value).
Helper.robotis_openCM70_sensor_value:
Final number of sound detection : the value of the final detected sound times.
Number of live sound detection : increases by 1 when it detects the next sound within 1 second.
Status of user button: the value of contact (1), non-contact (0).Final number of sound detection : the value of the number of last live sound detection.
Number of live sound detection : increases by 1 when it detects the next sound within 1 second.
Status of user button : the value of contact (1), non-contact (0).
Helper.robotis_openCM70_aux_sensor_value:
Position of servo motor: 0-1023, the value of the middle is 512.
Infrared sensor : the value is larger when it's close to an object.
Contact sensor: the value of contact(1), non-contact(0).
CDS: 0-1023, the value is larger when it's brighter.
Temperature-humidity sensor (humidity) : 0-100, the value is larger when it's more humid.
Temperature-humidity sensor (temperature) : -20 - 100, the value is larger when it's higher in temperature.
Temperature sensor : -20 - 100, the value is larger when it's higher in temperature.
Ultrasound sensor: -
Magnetic sensor : the value of contact(1), non-contact(0).
Motion detector: the value of detected motion(1), non-detected motion(0).
Color sensor: the value of unknown(0), white(1), black(2), red(3), green(4), blue(5), yellow(6).
User device: please refer to ROBOTIS e-manual (http://support.robotis.com/ko/) for the explanation on user sensor production.

Helper.robotis_openCM70_cm_motion: Executes the motion downloaded on the device.
Helper.robotis_openCM70_aux_motor_speed: Sets the speed of decelerating motor to the value of 0 - 1023.
Helper.robotis_openCM70_aux_servo_mode:
Sets the servo motor as wheel mode or joint mode.
The same mode continues to apply once it's set.
Wheel mode designates the servo motor's speed, and spins the servo motor.
Joint mode moves the servo motor's position with the set servo motor speed.

Helper.hamster_change_both_wheels_by: Adds the entered values to the current speed values (%) of the left and right wheels respectively. If the result is positive, the wheel rotates forward; if negative, the wheel rotates backward.
Helper.hamster_change_buzzer_by: Adds the entered value to the current pitch (Hz) of the buzzer sound. You can enter up to two decimal places.
Helper.hamster_change_output_by:
Adds the entered value to the current output value of the selected external port. The result will be in the following range depending on the mode of the external port.
Servo output: valid range from 1 to 180 degrees; if 0, output 0 without PWM pulse
PWM output: 0 to 100%, duty ratio (%) of ON state in PWM waveform
Digital output: LOW when 0, otherwise HIGH
Helper.hamster_change_tempo_by: Adds the entered value to the current BPM (beats per minute) of the playing or resting speed.
Helper.hamster_change_wheel_by: Adds the entered value to the current speed value (%) of the left/right/both wheels. If the result is positive, the wheel rotates forward; if negative, the wheel rotates backward.
Helper.hamster_follow_line_until: Moves along the black/white line on the left/right/front/back, then stops when the robot meets the intersection.
Helper.hamster_follow_line_using: Moves along the black/white line by using the left/right/both floor sensors.
Helper.hamster_hand_found: If there is a hand or object in front of the proximity sensor, true, otherwise false
Helper.hamster_move_backward_for_secs: Moves backward for the number of seconds entered.
Helper.hamster_move_forward_for_secs: Moves forward for the number of seconds entered.
Helper.hamster_move_forward_once: Moves one space forward on the board.
Helper.hamster_play_note_for: It sounds the selected tone and octave as much as the beat you entered.
Helper.hamster_rest_for: Rests as much as the beat you entered.
Helper.hamster_set_both_wheels_to: Sets the speed of the left and right wheels to the entered values (-100 to 100%), respectively. If you enter a positive value, the wheel rotates forward. If you enter a negative value, the wheel rotates backward. Entering the number 0 stops it.
Helper.hamster_set_buzzer_to: Sets the pitch of the buzzer sound to the entered value (Hz). You can enter up to two decimal places. Entering the number 0 turns off the buzzer sound.
Helper.hamster_set_following_speed_to: Sets the speed (1 to 8) to move along the line. The larger the number, the faster the movement.
Helper.hamster_set_led_to: Turns left/right/both LEDs to the selected color.
Helper.hamster_set_output_to:
Sets the output value of the selected external port to the entered value. The value has the following range according to the mode of external port.
Servo output: valid range from 1 to 180 degrees; if 0, output 0 without PWM pulse
PWM output: 0 to 100%, duty ratio (%) of ON state in PWM waveform
Digital output: LOW when 0, otherwise HIGH
Helper.hamster_set_port_to: Sets the io mode of the selected external port to the selected mode.
Helper.hamster_set_tempo_to: Sets the playing or resting speed to the entered BPM (beats per minute).
Helper.hamster_set_wheel_to: Sets the speed of the left/right/both wheels to the entered value (-100 to 100%). If you enter a positive value, the wheel rotates forward. If you enter a negative value, the wheel rotates backward. Entering the number 0 stops it.
Helper.hamster_turn_for_secs: Turns left/right for the number of seconds entered.
Helper.hamster_turn_once: Turns left/right 90 degrees on the board.
Helper.hamster_value:
left proximity: value of left proximity sensor (range: 0 to 255, initial value: 0)
right proximity: value of right proximity sensor (range: 0 to 255, initial value: 0)
left floor: value of left floor sensor (range: 0 to 100, initial value: 0)
right floor: value of right floor sensor (range: 0 to 100, initial value: 0)
x acceleration: x-axis value of acceleration sensor (range: -32768 to 32767, initial value: 0) The direction in which the robot moves forward is the positive direction of the x axis.
y acceleration: y-axis value of acceleration sensor (range: -32768 to 32767, initial value: 0) The left direction of the robot is the positive direction of the y axis.
z acceleration: z-axis value of acceleration sensor (range: -32768 to 32767, initial value: 0) The upward direction of the robot is the positive direction of the z axis.
light: value of light sensor (range: 0 to 65535, initial value: 0) The brighter, the larger the value.
temperature: temperature value inside the robot (range: -40 to 88 degrees Celsius, initial value: 0)
signal strength: signal strength of Bluetooth communication (range: -128 to 0 dBm, initial value: 0) As the signal strength increases, the value increases.
input A: value of signal input to external port A (range: analog input 0 to 255, digital input 0 or 1, initial value: 0)
input B: value of signal input to external port B (range: analog input 0 to 255, digital input 0 or 1, initial value: 0)
Helper.roboid_hamster_change_both_wheels_by: Adds the entered values to the current speed values (%) of the left and right wheels respectively. If the result is positive, the wheel rotates forward; if negative, the wheel rotates backward.
Helper.roboid_hamster_change_buzzer_by: Adds the entered value to the current pitch (Hz) of the buzzer sound. You can enter up to two decimal places.
Helper.roboid_hamster_change_output_by:
Adds the entered value to the current output value of the selected external port. The result will be in the following range depending on the mode of the external port.
Servo output: valid range from 1 to 180 degrees; if 0, output 0 without PWM pulse
PWM output: 0 to 100%, duty ratio (%) of ON state in PWM waveform
Digital output: LOW when 0, otherwise HIGH
Helper.roboid_hamster_change_tempo_by: Adds the entered value to the current BPM (beats per minute) of the playing or resting speed.
Helper.roboid_hamster_change_wheel_by: Adds the entered value to the current speed value (%) of the left/right/both wheels. If the result is positive, the wheel rotates forward; if negative, the wheel rotates backward.
Helper.roboid_hamster_follow_line_until: Moves along the black/white line on the left/right/front/back, then stops when the robot meets the intersection.
Helper.roboid_hamster_follow_line_using: Moves along the black/white line by using the left/right/both floor sensors.
Helper.roboid_hamster_hand_found: If there is a hand or object in front of the proximity sensor, true, otherwise false
Helper.roboid_hamster_move_backward_for_secs: Moves backward for the number of seconds entered.
Helper.roboid_hamster_move_forward_for_secs: Moves forward for the number of seconds entered.
Helper.roboid_hamster_move_forward_once: Moves one space forward on the board.
Helper.roboid_hamster_play_note_for: It sounds the selected tone and octave as much as the beat you entered.
Helper.roboid_hamster_rest_for: Rests as much as the beat you entered.
Helper.roboid_hamster_set_both_wheels_to: Sets the speed of the left and right wheels to the entered values (-100 to 100%), respectively. If you enter a positive value, the wheel rotates forward. If you enter a negative value, the wheel rotates backward. Entering the number 0 stops it.
Helper.roboid_hamster_set_buzzer_to: Sets the pitch of the buzzer sound to the entered value (Hz). You can enter up to two decimal places. Entering the number 0 turns off the buzzer sound.
Helper.roboid_hamster_set_following_speed_to: Sets the speed (1 to 8) to move along the line. The larger the number, the faster the movement.
Helper.roboid_hamster_set_led_to: Turns left/right/both LEDs to the selected color.
Helper.roboid_hamster_set_output_to:
Sets the output value of the selected external port to the entered value. The value has the following range according to the mode of external port.
Servo output: valid range from 1 to 180 degrees; if 0, output 0 without PWM pulse
PWM output: 0 to 100%, duty ratio (%) of ON state in PWM waveform
Digital output: LOW when 0, otherwise HIGH
Helper.roboid_hamster_set_port_to: Sets the io mode of the selected external port to the selected mode.
Helper.roboid_hamster_set_tempo_to: Sets the playing or resting speed to the entered BPM (beats per minute).
Helper.roboid_hamster_set_wheel_to: Sets the speed of the left/right/both wheels to the entered value (-100 to 100%). If you enter a positive value, the wheel rotates forward. If you enter a negative value, the wheel rotates backward. Entering the number 0 stops it.
Helper.roboid_hamster_turn_for_secs: Turns left/right for the number of seconds entered.
Helper.roboid_hamster_turn_once: Turns left/right 90 degrees on the board.
Helper.roboid_hamster_value:
left proximity: value of left proximity sensor (range: 0 to 255, initial value: 0)
right proximity: value of right proximity sensor (range: 0 to 255, initial value: 0)
left floor: value of left floor sensor (range: 0 to 100, initial value: 0)
right floor: value of right floor sensor (range: 0 to 100, initial value: 0)
x acceleration: x-axis value of acceleration sensor (range: -32768 to 32767, initial value: 0) The direction in which the robot moves forward is the positive direction of the x axis.
y acceleration: y-axis value of acceleration sensor (range: -32768 to 32767, initial value: 0) The left direction of the robot is the positive direction of the y axis.
z acceleration: z-axis value of acceleration sensor (range: -32768 to 32767, initial value: 0) The upward direction of the robot is the positive direction of the z axis.
light: value of light sensor (range: 0 to 65535, initial value: 0) The brighter, the larger the value.
temperature: temperature value inside the robot (range: -40 to 88 degrees Celsius, initial value: 0)
signal strength: signal strength of Bluetooth communication (range: -128 to 0 dBm, initial value: 0) As the signal strength increases, the value increases.
input A: value of signal input to external port A (range: analog input 0 to 255, digital input 0 or 1, initial value: 0)
input B: value of signal input to external port B (range: analog input 0 to 255, digital input 0 or 1, initial value: 0)
Helper.roboid_turtle_button_state: If the button clicked/double-clicked/long-pressed, true, otherwise false.
Helper.roboid_turtle_change_buzzer_by: Adds the entered value to the current pitch (Hz) of the buzzer sound. You can enter up to two decimal places.
Helper.roboid_turtle_change_head_led_by_rgb: Adds the entered values to the current R, G, B values of the head LED, respectively.
Helper.roboid_turtle_change_tempo_by: Adds the entered value to the current BPM (beats per minute) of the playing or resting speed.
Helper.roboid_turtle_change_wheel_by: Adds the entered value to the current speed value (%) of the left/right/both wheels. If the result is positive, the wheel rotates forward; if negative, the wheel rotates backward.
Helper.roboid_turtle_change_wheels_by_left_righ: Adds the entered values to the current speed values (%) of the left and right wheels respectively. If the result is positive, the wheel rotates forward; if negative, the wheel rotates backward.
Helper.roboid_turtle_cross_intersection: Moves forward for a moment at the black intersection, then finds the black line and moves again.
Helper.roboid_turtle_follow_line: Moves along the selected color line on a white background.
Helper.roboid_turtle_follow_line_until: Moves along the black line on a white background and stops when the color sensor detects the selected color.
Helper.roboid_turtle_follow_line_until_black: Moves along the selected color line on a white background and stops when the color sensor detects black.
Helper.roboid_turtle_is_color_pattern: If the color sensor detects the selected color pattern, true, otherwise false.
Helper.roboid_turtle_move_backward_unit: Moves backward for the number of cm/seconds/pulses entered.
Helper.roboid_turtle_move_forward_unit: Moves forward for the number of cm/seconds/pulses entered.
Helper.roboid_turtle_pivot_around_wheel_unit_in: Pivots around the left/right wheel in the head/tail direction for the number of degrees/seconds/pulses entered.
Helper.roboid_turtle_play_note: It sounds the selected tone and octave.
Helper.roboid_turtle_play_note_for_beats: It sounds the selected tone and octave as much as the beat you entered.
Helper.roboid_turtle_play_sound_times: Plays the selected sound as many times as entered.
Helper.roboid_turtle_play_sound_times_until_don: Plays the selected sound as many times as entered, and waits for completion.
Helper.roboid_turtle_rest_for_beats: Rests as much as the beat you entered.

Helper.roboid_turtle_set_following_speed_to: Sets the speed (1 to 8) to move along the line. The larger the number, the faster the movement.
Helper.roboid_turtle_set_head_led_to: Turns the head LED to the selected color.
Helper.roboid_turtle_set_head_led_to_rgb: Sets the R, G, B values of the head LED to the entered values.
Helper.roboid_turtle_set_tempo_to: Sets the playing or resting speed to the entered BPM (beats per minute).
Helper.roboid_turtle_set_wheel_to: Sets the speed of the left/right/both wheels to the entered value (-400 to 400%). If you enter a positive value, the wheel rotates forward. If you enter a negative value, the wheel rotates backward. Entering the number 0 stops it.
Helper.roboid_turtle_set_wheels_to_left_right: Sets the speed of the left and right wheels to the entered values (-400 to 400%), respectively. If you enter a positive value, the wheel rotates forward. If you enter a negative value, the wheel rotates backward. Entering the number 0 stops it.
Helper.roboid_turtle_touching_color: If the color sensor detects the selected color, true, otherwise false.
Helper.roboid_turtle_turn_at_intersection: Moves forward for a moment at the black intersection, then turns left/right/back in place, finds the black line and moves again.
Helper.roboid_turtle_turn_unit_in_place: Turns left/right in place for the number of degrees/seconds/pulses entered.
Helper.roboid_turtle_turn_unit_with_radius_in_d: Turns left/right drawing the circle of the entered radius in the head/tail direction for the number of degrees/seconds/pulses entered.

Helper.neobot_sensor_value: Indicates the input value from ports IN1 - IN3 and the battery information as number from 0 to 255.
Helper.neobot_sensor_convert_scale: The expressed scale of the selected port's change of input value as the value of a particular scale can be adjusted.
Helper.neobot_left_motor: Sets the wheel direction and speed of the motor connected to L motor port.
Helper.neobot_stop_left_motor: Stops the motor connected to L motor port.
Helper.neobot_right_motor: Sets the wheel direction and speed of the motor connected to R motor port.
Helper.neobot_stop_right_motor: Stops the motor connected to R motor port.
Helper.neobot_all_motor: The speed, time, and direction towards front, back, left and right, when connecting 2 motors to L and R motor ports can be set and used as wheels.
Helper.neobot_stop_all_motor: Stops the motor connected to both L and R motor ports.
Helper.neobot_set_servo: The angle within 0 - 180 degrees when connecting servo motor to OUT1 - OUT3 can be adjusted

Helper.neobot_set_fnd_off: Number indicated on FND can be turned off.

Helper.rotate_by_angle_dropdown: Rotates the object by the input number of degrees.
Helper.chocopi_control_button:
This block will be true if the button is pressed.


Port number(P1~P8) is automatically selected internally It is needed only when multiple modules with the same kind are used
Helper.chocopi_control_event:
You can attach blocks to process when the button is pressed or released


Port number(P1~P8) is automatically selected internally It is needed only when multiple modules with the same kind are used
Helper.chocopi_control_joystick:
Joystick X,Y and potentiometer has range of 0~4095.
so, around 2047 will be center value.


Port number(P1~P8) is automatically selected internally It is needed only when multiple modules with the same kind are used
Helper.chocopi_dc_motor:
Two DC motors can be connected to 'DC motor' module
The motor will be supplied with maximum 5V.
Maximum value is 100 (100%), is negative value is used then it will rotate opposite direction.

Port number(P1~P8) is automatically selected internally It is needed only when multiple modules with the same kind are used
Helper.chocopi_led:
LED number start from 1 and is the connecting order from the LED module.
You can assign RGB values from 0 to 255
RGB(Red Green Blue) order
To watch an LED with bright light can be painful,
so, please use small number like 0 to 5.

Port number(P1~P8) is automatically selected internally It is needed only when multiple modules with the same kind are used
Helper.chocopi_motion_photogate_event:
Two photogates can be connected to 'Motion' module
A photogate is a device with light sensor facing light source in opposite side
You can attach blocks when an object blocks or unblocks light sensor


Port number(P1~P8) is automatically selected internally It is needed only when multiple modules with the same kind are used
Helper.chocopi_motion_photogate_status:
Two photogates can be connected to 'Motion' module
A photogate is a device with light sensor facing light source in opposite side
This block will be true if an object blocks sensor

Port number(P1~P8) is automatically selected internally It is needed only when multiple modules with the same kind are used
Helper.chocopi_motion_photogate_time:
Two photogates can be connected to 'Motion' module
A photogate is a device with light sensor facing light source in opposite side
This block will have the time when an object blocked or unblocked the sensor
It can measure time with resolution of 1/10000 sec

Port number(P1~P8) is automatically selected internally It is needed only when multiple modules with the same kind are used
Helper.chocopi_motion_value:
'Motion' module has three infrared sensors
The value has range of 0~4095, the more reflection from object, the smaller the value is
It can be used to measure approximate distance between the sensor and an object
Acceleration and angular acceleration value ranges from -32768 to 32767.
You can measure inclination of the sensor using these values.

Port number(P1~P8) is automatically selected internally It is needed only when multiple modules with the same kind are used
Helper.chocopi_sensor:
Temperature value is Celsius.
Relative humidity value ranges from 0 to 100%.
Light value ranges 0~4095 in log scale.
Analog value ranges from 0 to 4095.

Port number(P1~P8) is automatically selected internally. It is needed only when multiple modules with the same kind are used
Helper.chocopi_servo_motor:
'Servo' module can be connected to four servo motors
Servo motors are provided with 5V
You can assign 0~200 in degree unit.
If a contineous rotational servo motor is connected, it's speed is determined by the degree value.
Center value is from 90 to 100 varying by motor model.

Port number(P1~P8) is automatically selected internally It is needed only when multiple modules with the same kind are used
Helper.chocopi_touch_event:
Touch module has #1~12 connecting pads.
You can attach block to process when these pads are touched or untouched.


Port number(P1~P8) is automatically selected internally It is needed only when multiple modules with the same kind are used
Helper.chocopi_touch_status:
It will be true if the pad is touched.


Port number(P1~P8) is automatically selected internally It is needed only when multiple modules with the same kind are used
Helper.chocopi_touch_value:
The value will be smaller if the capacitance of the obeject is larger.
If many people hold each other's hand and touch, the value will be smaller
'Capacitance' means how many electric particles the object can hold.


Port number(P1~P8) is automatically selected internally It is needed only when multiple modules with the same kind are used
Helper.boolean_and_or:
AND : Checks whether both conditions are true.
OR : Checks whether at least one of the two conditions is true.
Helper.check_weather: Checks whether the weather information of the selected date and region matches the actual weather conditions.
Helper.check_finedust: Checks whether the current fine dust information of the selected region matches the actual fine dust grade.
Helper.get_weather_data: Reports various weather information values (the lowest temperature, the highest temperature, humidity, precipitation, precipitation probability, wind speed) of the selected date and region.
Helper.get_current_weather_data: Reports the current weather information (temperature, fine dust grade) of the selected region.
Helper.get_today_temperature: Reports the today temperature of selected area and time zone.
Helper.check_city_weather: Checks whether the weather information of the selected date and region matches the actual weather conditions.
Helper.check_city_finedust: Checks whether the current fine dust information of the selected region matches the actual fine dust grade.
Helper.get_city_weather_data: Reports various weather information values (the lowest temperature, the highest temperature, humidity, precipitation, precipitation probability, wind speed) of the selected date and region.
Helper.get_current_city_weather_data: Reports the current weather information (temperature, fine dust grade) of the selected region.
Helper.get_today_city_temperature: Report the today temperature of selected area and time zone.
Helper.count_festival: Translate the input text into the selected language. You can enter up to 20 charactors.
Helper.get_festival_info: Detects the language of the input text. You can enter up to 20 charactors.
Helper.get_translated_string: The number of events held on the selected date and region.
Helper.check_language: Reports the information(Title, area, start date, end date, address, overview, homepage) about events held on the selected date and region.
Helper.count_disaster_behavior: The number of behavior-guideline's when selected natural disaster occurs.
Helper.get_disaster_behavior: Reports the information about behavior-guidelines when selected natural disaster occurs.
Helper.count_lifeSafety_behavior: The number of behavior-guideline's when selected life problem occurs.
Helper.get_lifeSafety_behavior: Reports the information about behavior-guidelines when selected life problem occurs.
Helper.read_text: Read the entered text in setted voice.
Helper.set_tts_property:
Set the selected voice to selected speed and selected pitch. 
 The selected voice will be set up to selected speed and selected pitch.
Helper.read_text_wait_with_block: Read the entered text in setted voice then the next block runs after the reading finished.
Helper.speech_to_text_convert: Converts person's speech input through microphone into text.
Helper.speech_to_text_get_value: Reports the value of the person's speech to text. If no speech is input or an error occurs during recognition, it will report null values.
Helper.get_microphone_volume: Reports the volume of sound input through microphone.
Helper.video_draw_webcam: Show or hide the video screen. (IE / iOS Not Supported)
Helper.video_check_webcam: Check whether video is connected with the computer. (IE / iOS Not Supported)
Helper.video_change_cam: Switch the camera that input video.
Helper.video_set_camera_opacity_option: Set the transparency effect to the video screen by the input value.(IE / iOS Not Supported)
Helper.video_flip_camera: Flips the video screen horizontally or vertically. (IE / iOS Not Supported)
Helper.video_toggle_model: Start or stop the selected recognition model. Face Recognition: Recognizes a person's face to know where the eyes, nose, mouth, and ear are located, or the expected gender, age, and emotion. Human Recognition: Recognizes a person's body to know where each part is located Object Recognition: Shows the recognized object type. (Person or thing) (IE / iOS Not Supported)
Helper.video_toggle_ind: Show location and index of the detected humans/faces/objects on the screen. (IE / iOS Not Supported)
Helper.video_number_detect: Reports number of humans/faces/objects detected on the video screen. (IE / iOS Not Supported)
Helper.video_object_detected: Check whether selected object is recognized. (IE / iOS Not Supported)
Helper.video_is_model_loaded: Check whether human/face/object is detected. (IE / iOS Not Supported)
Helper.video_detected_face_info: Reports the estimated value of the selected face area among the faces in the input order. If it is not recognized, it is outputted as 0 unconditionally. (Gender, Age, Emotion)  (IE / iOS Not Supported)
Helper.video_motion_value: Reports the motion or direction value detected on the selected object or screen.  (IE / iOS Not Supported)
Helper.video_face_part_coord: Reports the position value of the selected face area among the faces in the input order. If it is not recognized, it is outputted as 0 unconditionally. (Left eye, Right eye, Nose, Left mouse, Right mouse, Top Lip, Bottom Lip)  (IE / iOS Not Supported)
Helper.video_body_part_coord: Reports number of human detected on the video screen. (Face, Right shoulder, Right elbow, Right wrist, Left shoulder, Left elbow, Left wrist, Right hip, Right knee, Right ankle, Left hip, Left knee, Left ankle)  (IE / iOS Not Supported)
Helper.append_row_to_table: Adds a row(col) to the end location of the selected table.
Helper.insert_row_to_table: Adds a row (column) to the entered order of the selected table. All cell values ​​in the added row (column) are 0. The rows (columns) after the added row (column) are pushed back one by one.
Helper.delete_row_from_table: Deletes the row (column) in the entered order of the selected table.
Helper.set_value_from_table: Replaces the attribute of the entered row with the values ​​entered in the selected table.
Helper.save_current_table: Keep the table as it is. Even if you stop the project, your changes in the table are maintained.
Helper.get_table_count: The number of rows (columns) in the selected table.
Helper.get_value_from_table: The selected attribute value of the entered row in the selected table. Instead of an attribute value block, you can also combine a value block (meaning a row).
Helper.get_value_from_last_row: The selected attribute value of the last row in the selected table. Instead of an attribute value block, you can also combine a value block (meaning a row).
Helper.calc_values_from_table: Reports calculated value of the selected attributes in the selected table. (sum, maximum, minimum, average, standard deviation)
Helper.open_table: Open the window of the selected table.
Helper.open_table_wait: Open the window of the selected table for the seconds entered.
Helper.open_table_chart: Opens the chart of the selected table.
Helper.change_rgb_to_hex: Reports the value of the entered red, green, and blue values converted to HEX value.
Helper.change_hex_to_rgb: Reports the HEX value entered converted to either red, green, or blue.
Helper.insert_data_for_test: Enters the data and classifies using the trained model.
Helper.insert_text_block_for_test: Classifies the entered value ​​using the trained model.
Helper.test_result: This is the classification result of the entered data using the model. The resulting value is expressed as the model's class name (text).
Helper.accuracy_of_result: This is the confidence score for the selected class of the entered data. The values ​​are expressed in numbers.
Helper.is_group: Determines 'True' if the classification result of the data entered is the selected class.
Helper.retrain_model: Retrains the model. If you have changed the model settings, or have modified the contents of the table consisting the input data, the model is retrained based on the changed contents.
Helper.model_is_trained: If the model has trained, it is determined as 'True'. If the model is being trained or hasn't trained, it is determined as 'False'.
Helper.set_train_visible: Shows or hides the window displaying the state of the model on the screen.
Helper.set_train_chart: Opens or closes the chart window that displays the train data and clusters of the trained model on a two-dimensional coordinate plane.
Helper.set_regression_option: Changes the model's training condition. The changed training condition is applied when the model is retrained with the'Retrain model' block.
Helper.get_regression_predict_1: Returns the value predicted by the model using the entered feature value.
Helper.get_regression_predict_2: Returns the value predicted by the model using the entered feature value.
Helper.get_regression_predict_3: Returns the value predicted by the model using the entered feature value.
Helper.get_regression_accuracy: Returns the model's coefficient of determination as a value.
Helper.set_cluster_option_k: Sets the number of clusters by replacing them with the entered value. The changed number of clusters will be applied when the model is retrained with the 'Retrain model' block.
Helper.set_cluster_option_centroids: Changes the standard of the cluster's initial centroid with the standard selected. The changed centroid standard is applied when the model is retrained with the 'Retrain model' block.
Helper.get_cluster_centriod_count: Returns the number of clusters in the model as a value.
Helper.get_cluster_centriod_value: Returns the feature value for the the centroid of the specified cluster. If you have multiple features, you can select them from the drop-down list.
Helper.get_cluster_centriod_index_1: Returns which cluster the entered feature value belongs to among the clustered clusters by the model. Values ​​are expressed as text (cluster name).
Helper.get_cluster_centriod_index_2: Returns which cluster the entered feature value belongs to among the clustered clusters by the model. Values ​​are expressed as text (cluster name).
Helper.get_cluster_centriod_index_3: Returns which cluster the entered feature value belongs to among the clustered clusters by the model. Values ​​are expressed as text (cluster name).
Helper.set_number_learning_option_k: Sets the number of of neighbors by replacing them with the entered value. The changed number of neighbors will be applied when the model is retrained wirh the 'Retrain model' block.
Helper.get_number_learning_predict_1: The result value of the classification of the data entered by the model. The value is expressed by the class name (text).
Helper.get_number_learning_predict_2: The result value of the classification of the data entered by the model. The value is expressed by the class name (text).
Helper.get_number_learning_predict_3: The result value of the classification of the data entered by the model. The value is expressed by the class name (text).
Helper.get_number_learning_predict_param_1: The classification confidence score for the selected class of the data entered. The value is expressed in numbers.

Helper.roboid_hamster_s_change_both_wheels_by: Adds the entered values to the current speed values (%) of the left and right wheels respectively. If the result is positive, the wheel rotates forward; if negative, the wheel rotates backward.
Helper.roboid_hamster_s_set_both_wheels_to: Sets the speed of the left and right wheels to the entered values (-100 to 100%), respectively. If you enter a positive value, the wheel rotates forward. If you enter a negative value, the wheel rotates backward. Entering the number 0 stops it.
Helper.roboid_hamster_s_change_wheel_by: Adds the entered value to the current speed value (%) of the left/right/both wheels. If the result is positive, the wheel rotates forward; if negative, the wheel rotates backward.
Helper.roboid_hamster_s_set_wheel_to: Sets the speed of the left/right/both wheels to the entered value (-100 to 100%). If you enter a positive value, the wheel rotates forward. If you enter a negative value, the wheel rotates backward. Entering the number 0 stops it.
Helper.roboid_hamster_s_follow_line_using: Moves along the black/white line by using the left/right/both floor sensors.
Helper.roboid_hamster_s_follow_line_until: Moves along the black/white line on the left/right/front/back, then stops when the robot meets the intersection.
Helper.roboid_hamster_s_set_following_speed_to: Sets the speed (1 to 8) to move along the line. The larger the number, the faster the movement.
Helper.roboid_hamster_s_set_following_gain_to: Sets the directional variation (1 to 8) 선을 따라 이동하는 방향 변화량(1 ~ 8)을 설정합니다. 숫자가 클수록 급커브를 잘 따라가지만 직선에서 좌우로 더 흔들립니다.
Helper.roboid_hamster_s_set_led_to: Turns left/right/both LEDs to the selected color.
Helper.roboid_hamster_s_pick_led: Turns left/right/both LEDs to the selected color.
Helper.roboid_hamster_s_change_led_by_rgb: Adds the entered values to the current R, G, B values of left/right/both LEDs, respectively.
Helper.roboid_hamster_s_set_led_to_rgb: Sets the R, G, B values of left/right/both LEDs to the entered values.
Helper.roboid_hamster_s_play_sound_times: Plays the selected sound as many times as entered.
Helper.roboid_hamster_s_play_sound_times_until_: Plays the selected sound as many times as entered, and waits for completion.
Helper.roboid_hamster_s_change_buzzer_by: Adds the entered value to the current pitch (Hz) of the buzzer sound. You can enter up to two decimal places.
Helper.roboid_hamster_s_set_buzzer_to: Sets the pitch of the buzzer sound to the entered value (Hz). You can enter up to two decimal places. Entering the number 0 turns off the buzzer sound.
Helper.roboid_hamster_s_play_note: It sounds the selected tone and octave.
Helper.roboid_hamster_s_play_note_for: It sounds the selected tone and octave as much as the beat you entered.
Helper.roboid_hamster_s_rest_for: Rests as much as the beat you entered.
Helper.roboid_hamster_s_change_tempo_by: Adds the entered value to the current BPM (beats per minute) of the playing or resting speed.
Helper.roboid_hamster_s_set_tempo_to: Sets the playing or resting speed to the entered BPM (beats per minute).
Helper.roboid_hamster_s_set_port_to: Sets the io mode of the selected external port to the selected mode.
Helper.roboid_hamster_s_change_output_by:
Adds the entered value to the current output value of the selected external port. The result will be in the following range depending on the mode of the external port.
Servo output: valid range from 1 to 180 degrees; if 0, output 0 without PWM pulse
PWM output: 0 to 100%, duty ratio (%) of ON state in PWM waveform
Digital output: LOW when 0, otherwise HIGH
Helper.roboid_hamster_s_set_output_to:
Sets the output value of the selected external port to the entered value. The value has the following range according to the mode of external port.
Servo output: valid range from 1 to 180 degrees; if 0, output 0 without PWM pulse
PWM output: 0 to 100%, duty ratio (%) of ON state in PWM waveform
Digital output: LOW when 0, otherwise HIGH
Helper.roboid_hamster_s_release_gripper: Turns off the gripper so that it can be moved freely.
Helper.roboid_hamster_s_read_serial_until: Read the strings received by serial communication.
Helper.roboid_hamster_s_set_serial_rate_to: Sets the speed of serial communication.

color g: green component of color detected by the color sensor (range: 0 ~ 255, initial value: 0)
color b: blue component of color detected by the color sensor (range: 0 ~ 255, initial value: 0)
floor: value of floor sensor (range: 0 to 100, initial value: 0)
button: status of the button (when pressed 1, otherwise 0, initial value: 0)
x acceleration: x-axis value of acceleration sensor (range: -32768 to 32767, initial value: 0) The direction in which the robot moves forward is the positive direction of the x axis.
y acceleration: y-axis value of acceleration sensor (range: -32768 to 32767, initial value: 0) The left direction of the robot is the positive direction of the y axis.
z acceleration: z-axis value of acceleration sensor (range: -32768 to 32767, initial value: 0) The upward direction of the robot is the positive direction of the z axis.
temperature: temperature value inside the robot (range: -41 to 87 degrees Celsius, initial value: 0)
signal strength: signal strength of Bluetooth communication (range: -128 to 0 dBm, initial value: 0) As the signal strength increases, the value increases.

Helper.media_pipe_video_screen: Shows or hides the video screen.
Helper.media_pipe_switch_camera: Switches the camera that films the video.
Helper.check_connected_camera: Checks whether camera is conncected with the computer. If the camera is connected to the computer, it is judged as 'True'.
Helper.media_pipe_flip_camera: Flips the video screen horizontally or vertically.
Helper.media_pipe_set_opacity_camera:
Sets the transparency effect of video screen to the input value. It can be set in the range from 0 to 100.
(The default value is 50. Values under 0 is treated as 0 and over 100 is treated as 100.)
Helper.media_pipe_motion_value:
Reports the motion or direction value detected on the selected object or screen.
- Motion: The larger and faster the movement, the larger the value.
- Direction: Positive when moving right or up, and negative when moving left or down
Helper.when_pose_landmarker: When human detected, the connected blocks below will run.
Helper.pose_landmarker:
Start or stop the human detection model.
- Human Detection: Detects a human and determines where each body parts are located.
Helper.draw_detected_pose: Shows or hides the location and order of the detected humans on the screen.
Helper.check_detected_pose: If the human is detected, it is judged as 'True'.
Helper.count_detected_pose: Reports the number of the humans detected on the video screen.
Helper.locate_to_pose: Moves the object to the position of the selected body part.
Helper.locate_time_to_pose: Moves the object to the position of the selected body part for the input seconds.
Helper.axis_detected_pose:
Reports the location value of the selected body part of the human in the order entered.
(Body parts: face, neck, left eye, right eye, left ear, right ear, left shoulder, right shoulder, left elbow, right elbow, left wirst, right wrist, left hip, right hip, left knee, right knee, left ankle, right ankle)
Helper.when_face_landmarker: When face detected, the connected blocks below will run.
Helper.face_landmarker:
Start or stop the face detection model.
- Face Detection: Detects a human's face and determines where the eyes, nose, mouth, and ear are located.
Helper.draw_detected_face: Shows or hides the location and order of the detected faces on the screen.
Helper.check_detected_face: If the face is detected, it is judged as 'True'.
Helper.count_detected_face: Reports the number of the faces detected on the video screen.
Helper.locate_to_face: Moves the object to the position of the selected face part.
Helper.locate_time_to_face: Moves the object to the position of the selected body part for the input seconds.
Helper.check_detected_gender: If the selected face is the selected gender, it is judged as 'True'.
Helper.check_compare_age: If the age of the selected face matches the formula, it is judged as 'True'.
Helper.check_detected_emotion: If the selected face is the selected emotion, it is judged as 'True'.
Helper.axis_detected_face: Reports the location value of the selected face area of the face in the order entered. (Face area: left eye, right eye, nose, left corner of lips, right corner of lips, upper lip, lower lip)
Helper.get_detected_face_value: Reports the estimated value of the gender/age/emotion of the face in the order entered. If it is not detected, it returns 0.
